segments.text: Didn't have Somerville.
And I thought, gee, if we've got that east of town, and I didn't know whether any of that bottom land was any good or not, well, gee, that would be great.
But it never came about.
Who were Mr.
Rudder's?
Before I lose this thought, talking about lakes, he was all for Lake Somerville.
And the honcho on that project was one Hub Baker from Somerville, Texas,
and his brother Eddie.
They were big heavy boys, big eaters.
And they were nearly as close with LBJ as Mr.
Rudder was.
And they bought up the land around the AWOL there and then suggested maybe that a lake would be nice there.
Well, it so happens that Overlook Marina, which he developed and owned, happened to be on the high prominence right next to the dam.
And so strangely enough, that dam was built.
And Hub Baker was right in the middle of the money part of it.
And somehow Mr. Rutter knew Hub.
And one day, when the dam had been built, they were going to have a gigantic opening celebration.
And Lyndon Johnson was going to be a speaker, and Jake Pickle, and others.
And I was in the office.
And Hub called Earl Rutter and said,
Earl, we're going to have this thing over here you know Johnson's behind it and we're behind it and all that and it's going to be a real bone to your school.
People will have places to swim and fish and boat and ski.
He said, we want the Aggie band.
He said, Hub, when is this thing going to take place?
And he said, June the 4th.
And Mr.
Rudder looked at me and he says, Edwin, is there an Aggie band on June the 4th?
I said, no, sir, there is not.
there is no Aggie band in the summer.
And he reported that to Hub, and Hub just really got mad.
And he said, well, you, he said, that's your part, Earl.
He said, you got to have the music here.
I don't care.
If you can't have the Aggie band, you get something.
And Mr.
Rudder looked at me and said, Edwin, you are the music director for the grand opening of Lake Somerville.
He said, you get over there and get with Hub Baker and get that old man off my back.
And I went to about 15 meetings.
And when the
the celebration took place, I had the Glenn College Band.
I had the A&M Consolidated Band, the Bryan High School Band, the Somerville Band, the Branham Band.
We had six bands there.
And LBJ didn't show up.
And they had made such an elaborate grandstand according to Secret Service guidelines for the president.
It was two stories high.
And they had that thing built down there, according to the specs.
And boy, they're just unbelievable specs.
The one they were going to do for President Ford, I think, on Kyle Field, minimum cost $32,000 for the grandstand.
I looked into that for graduation.
But Hub, we went on with the celebration.
And Jake Pickle was the main speaker.

and hub had that grandstand hauled up on the hill behind his marina screened it in and had a two-story cabin for rent i think it's still over there can you remember any great frustrations mr rudder felt projects dreams he had that he wasn't able to bring to reality
I think two of the things that were really tough to solve would have been the formation of Connolly Tech.
Mr. Connolly said, Earl, do something with that place over there.
He said, I'm going to make it part of A&M, legally.
And you figure out what we can do over there.
James Connolly Technical Institute.
And they hired a guy named Roy Duggar.
And they developed the program there.
But how it fit in with A&M's mission was never, ever resolved.
So I think that one was really frustrating because of his allegiance versus what in the hell are we going to do with a technical institute?
And then the other one would have been A&M Galveston.
I can't remember exactly when that started.
I don't.
But, you know, it's still a... Lots of vice presidents have really worried over that one.
Who does it belong to?
Is it a college or is it on its own?
And those were two things that I know that he really worried about because he didn't
He really, I think, a real frustration was there were those that wanted A&M to be all things to all people.
And his feeling really truly was it's at College Station, Texas.
Now, you left his staff in 67.
In 67, I became director of civilian student activities.
And his charge to me was simple.
He said, I don't want to lose you in this office.
But we're going to have all these civilian students.
And I want you to go over there and study and think and talk and find out what we can do to give them a flagpole to rally around.
And one of the first things I did was visit LSU, Penn State, Purdue, and VPI, which were land grant schools.
I said, what do you do with non-core students?
And we developed the resident hall
program.
And boy, it hit the fan when he found out that it was going to cost some money.
But in my report to him, I showed him how we could finance it through student activity fees legally.
And it wasn't really that much money.
And I said, if you don't want to do it all at once, let's put names on those dormitories instead of numbers, instead of dorm.

16 let's make it Davis Gary Hall which put the name up that's the first thing and we did that and I said we'll get three pilot dormitories and we'll get one of each kind of dorm we have namely Leggett Walton and Davis Gary
and see if it will work there and get the students to help.
Set up a resident advisor program.
Instead of one guy responsible for 250 yahoos, we'd have four or five student employees in there.
And set up the first residence hall program.
And I think not many people know that that was my baby.

and uh and how it happened and so forth and uh to see it still alive now is something that i take pride in one of the things i wanted to give you is for the archives here's my report to president rutter on establishing the uh residence hall program this goes to the archive that goes to the world great that's the only
And it has the financing and who we took up to Lake Buchanan and had a retreat, including Charles McCandless and Atlantis Hope.
But there's how the whole thing got started right there.
And that I have no more use for here.
And that should be in the archives.
All right.
Just a couple of things before we break for lunch.
We now know when Mr.
Rudder died.
Were you, as a person that worked with him closely, were you aware of any declining health on his part not long before his attack?
At the moment of his attack was the second time that I had resigned from the university.
I did it twice, once before coming to his office and once after doing this work.
I was frustrated about the future and a lot of things, and I again left.
And while I was gone, I was with the American Oil Company in Bryan.
And when he had all that problem, I was not on campus.
And then Mr. Heaton was made dean, and they wanted a director of admissions, and that's when I came back.
And that's after Mr. Heaton.
That's after.
And I have a real fine letter from Frank Hubert and one from Horace Byers.
thanking me for helping with, even though I didn't work there any longer, helping with certain aspects of the funeral service.
Dick Bernard was his assistant at that time.
All right.
Summarize your feelings about Earl Rudder.
If you would allow me, I would say if you put the two together of Jack Williams and Earl Rudder, two very different types of personalities, we have in that combination
I think maybe a gift from heaven in the two of them.
One, finishing, in a sense, what the other one started and knowing how to do it.
The academic part that was a frustration to Mr. Rutter, Williams knew.
But he was hard-headed, stubborn, sweet, mean.

could be sarcastic, but was probably the single most important man in the history of the school based on what he visioned and having the good sense to go to academic type people and say, where should we be?
Knowing that he couldn't do that himself, he went to people that could.
So with the action he started, his willingness to go into
the changes, the dramatic changes of the 60s, his willingness to go along and support it, though it wasn't really the way he wanted it, shows the bigness of the man.
And he had the background and the friends out there to get the job done any day.
I'm sure he did it.
Let's chat now about Jack Kenny Williams.
You had, in 67, gone over to admissions.
Yeah, director of admissions.
And so let's cover that.
Did you follow Mr. Heaton immediately?
Yes.
And now, wait a minute.
Let's see.
I was director of admissions.
Mr. Heaton was dean.
Oh, OK.
So when you go.
Williams came in, and Williams asked Buckwires who a person would be that would be a good assistant for him.
He recommended me, and I went over there, leaving director of admissions position.
And Mr. Heaton said he was the only person in the world that ever called me Eddie.
Nobody has ever called me Eddie.
He says, Eddie, I just want you to find a person to take your place, someone as good as you've been.
I said, OK.
So I somehow made contact with Billie Jean Lay.
And it worked out just beautifully.
Bill made a fine director of admissions.
And then I served two years.
And then Mr. Heaton retired.
And I think you were probably helpful with me getting into that position.
And so I left the president's office and became dean of admissions.
Let's go back, though, when you first went over to work with Mr. Heaton.
What was the search process, as far as you know?
You mean for me to?
Yeah, how did?
The search process was Bob Lacey saying to Mr. Heaton,
We sure miss old Cooper here on campus.
We need to get him back.
And Mr. Heath says, would you go talk with Eddie and see if he?
Well, I was dying for a job on campus.
And that just worked perfectly.
So I'm sure that Bob Lacy is the one.
I think he said something like, don't hire anybody but Cooper.
That's what he said.
Describe this man.
How long had he been there?
What was he like?
He had been there since 1936.
And he was the most conservative, gentlemanly type of man that I have ever known.
Deep East Texas, from a big family.
Dressed to the T, I'll never forget
taking some catalogs to him on a Saturday morning.
He was mowing the grass and had on a long-sleeved white shirt and a tie tucked in between the buttons while he was mowing.
He worried about everything.
He worried about the women wearing slacks while at work.
until someone pointed out to him that when they bent over in a skirt to open the lower file cabinet that actually a lot of flesh was exposed.
And at that point, he agreed, well, maybe they should be allowed to wear slacks at work.
He was of the old school that felt that it would be terrifying to let this place grow too rapidly.
And he took a great pride in reporting to the president that it would look like we probably are going to be up 100 to 150 students this year.
And that just tickled him to death.
The part about girls coming in, he was so alarmed about that that it took three years for him to agree to finally put something in the catalog that wives of, well,
That never was put in there, I don't think.
And finally, after the third year, they said all students were admitted equally.
And he was under great suspect of any faculty wife, for example, that came in.
He just formed a moral judgment on each one of them.
And he stayed awake at night worrying about somebody fooling him about whether or not they really were eligible to be admitted.
set him back and he was generally opposed to international students and did everything he could really to make them unwelcome.
And you had a lot of leeway there because it's a judgment call.
From one country, a grade of 10 on a transcript is excellent.
On another, that's about as low as you can get and who is to argue with it?
Not many people know how to argue with that.
He was ultra-conservative about staff people, wanted to work with as few as humanly possible.
The admissions people were always overworked.
They'd stay up there until 7 or 8 o'clock at night trying to keep up with the applications once coeducation came along and so forth.
And the foreign students, when I went in there, nobody really was in charge.
And there's an interesting story, sideline there.
Jack Williams called me down one day and he said, do you believe in honoring commitments that other people have made?
I said, generally, yes.
He said, well, L.F. Peterson told Lloyd Taylor

that if he went to Tarleton and was athletic director and coach there and it worked and they got a big program going and people actually paying to see football games, that that would be a great service for the NM system.
And it worked out where Jesus himself could not have gotten a first-class football program at Tarleton.
And it cost Lloyd most of his stomach in turmoil and what do you call a stomach problem?
the ailment that you get when your stomach is ulcerated and so forth.
At any rate, they removed most of his stomach.
And that didn't work.
So he called through his own little way to find out if Mr. Peterson's promise that he could always come back to A&M, if anybody was going to uphold that, though Mr. Peterson was gone.
And Williams explained all of that to me.
And he said, did you know all that?
And I said, no, sir, I did not.
And he said, well, I'm going to honor the promise that was made in good faith.
He said, is there some way that you could work him into a spot in your organization where he would do good work?
I said, you bet.
So we met at the circle at the elite cafe in downtown Waco.
And I said, Lloyd, would you be interested in taking over the admission of international students?
I need some strength there.
And he agreed to and did a fine job and offered to take three or four Iranians out into the hallway and settle matters bare knuckles if that's what they really wanted.
And the word got out pretty well that you don't fool Mr. Taylor.
So I deviated, but that was it.
In all of your years
where you were responsible at whatever level for admissions.
Was it common for some higher administrator to let you know that a certain student was to be admitted regardless of their qualifications?
I don't think I ever had a president or a vice president say to me,
Or Bob Cherry is the one that had the most calls because the regents, I used to get mad at him, but that wasn't fair because they put it on him.
I finally had an agreement even with Bob Cherry.

I said, when you get under pressure like that, kind of stall a little bit and then let me come back to you and tell you after we study this case whether we think the child has a chance to stay until Halloween.
That was the date I used.
I said, now I'm going to tell you what I think, but I understand the pressure you're under, and we might have to swallow this one, but I'm going to tell you what I think.
And do you know that most of the time he'd go back and say to Royce or whoever it was, Cooper says, I don't think that child is going to last until Halloween because XXX.
And nine out of ten times he'd say, well, forget it.
So I can't say I had a, but I did have a lot of pressure on the first grievous error I ever made that I will admit, and that is getting housing on campus for students who were not entitled to it.
And I got the reputation for being able to do that, and it came down on me like bricks.
Housing was the biggest issue.
problem I faced in terms of tying it in with admission.
They would say things like, how can you admit my granddaughter and then tell her that she has to live in Bryan?
How can you do that?
That was the toughest thing.
And the president's office even said, OK, no more exceptions on housing.
If you get them, you just let us know and we'll decide.
And that didn't work.
Because that put the president's office in a very, very awkward situation.
And they found out very quickly that it's not an easy thing to manage.
Veterinary admissions were not your worry.
That's correct.
Nor medical school.
Nor medical school.
And the other majors.
And the graduate students, of course.
We processed, Ms. Dean processed it.
But the department and deans made the decisions.
And be it architecture, engineering, or whatever, those were decided internally once the student was in the institution.
So you didn't have to worry much with those.
That's right.
Let's see.
During those years that you were over there either the first or second time,
who were the key people in the area of registrar the registrars and director admissions areas just one minute i can i've got that here for you born around the world when that one died
Remember when I got you to make that speech?
We had dinner at your house.
I'll be over there.
Art, describe these people and their characteristics.
Bob Lacy.
Bob Lacy was, above all other things, loyal.
And when it came time to look at computerized registration, we were way ahead of most schools.
And he went to places like Purdue and BYU and learned the system and came back all excited.
And he said, he always called me Dean Cooper, though we were very close friends.
He said, within a year or two, there will not be a paper in this office.
Everything will be on computer.
And I said, Bob?
Not as long as I have this job.
I said, we can register on computer, but I want you to know that as long as I'm here, there will be a piece of cardboard down in the basement with the grades recorded on it.
We're going to have a paper backup and I don't want somebody coming in and saying the system is out and it ate everything in there.
I'm not going to do that.
So I think it's still that way, but Bob Lacey would do anything within reason.
And yet he would put up good arguments.
And I could say, now, Bob, you're right.
We shouldn't do this.
But let me tell you the spot I'm in.
And this vice president or this former student has asked us if we would do this.
And I'm telling you, for the long run, I think we better do it.
OK, that's the answer.
And then he would go to Don Carter under him and tell Don to do it.
And Don would go through a swamp of alligators with .50 calibers overhead and just say, which way are we supposed to go?
Rough as he could be in many ways around the edges, Don Carter is probably the most dedicated guy that I've ever had working for me.
He could make people mad because he was brusque, but he would do whatever you asked him to do.
Once he decided that that's the way it was going to be, then he'd start fussing.
And he grew up in a big urban city named Splendora.
Splendora, where the most exciting day of the year was the opening day of squirrel season.
So he could go out and hunt his beloved limb rats.
Now, let's see, and Miss Mitchell.
Miss Mitchell was a study unto herself.
She minced no words.

was so dedicated that one day when she collapsed on the floor by her desk and had an intestinal ailment, flu of some sort that caused her to collapse, we sent across, we were in Heaton Hall and got the, Pat, I think was his last name, one of the administrators to come over and he gave her a shot and she started feeling a little better but still couldn't get up.
reached up onto the desk and pulled a stack of transfer applications to the floor with her and continued her business until noon on the floor with a red pencil.
The most dedicated human I've ever seen, but did it by the step, piece by piece, course by course, and if it took 40 hours, that's what she did.
Now, she worked her entire adult life, didn't she, for you?
She was born on the NM campus in one of the old faculty houses.
Her husband was in the math department and bought up some property, and she was well-fixed all of her life.
And she just loved that work, and she knew transfer admissions better than anybody in Texas, without question.
And I believe that... And could make people mad.
I believe the sale of her estate possessions is tomorrow.
Yeah, right.
I think there is one.
Her mouth would get her in trouble once in a while.
She could be so blunt.
Some little girl, I said, please help this young lady.
Dr. Williams has called about her, and she is a house guest at the Williams right now, and I'd like for you to put hers on top of the stack.
And then she said to the little girl something like, well, I guess you know you wouldn't be here if you weren't the president's pet or something like that.
And Jack Williams came over to my office and broke through the door without knocking.
He says, who is Caroline Mitchell?
I said, Dr. Williams, you don't want to know.
I said, tell me what you want me to do and I will do it.
So we got an apology.
All right, let's go to Williams.
You were not part of his staff immediately.
When did you first interact with him?
What was your first impression?
He brought a word of greetings to the faculty at, what function was it at G. Raleigh White?
Was it a, what function was it?
Was it, could it have been the Faculty Achievements Award?
No, that would have been too late.
Because he began November 1, 1970.
Mr. Rutter died in March.
And Williams is here November 1, 1970.
And I came very quickly, became his assistant.
And that's what I was when I went to this program.
And he told his famous joke about the bricklayer that kept going up and down.
Yes, yes.
I thought, what a delightful human being in terms of holding an audience totally in his grasp.
And he said just the right things to the academic group that was there.
And I said, we're off and running.
We've got a sure enough winner here.
And of course, that position solidified.
The thing that I learned about him is that he was really temperamental.
but was able generally to hold his tongue until he was out in the hallway.
But one, for example, I had to meet him at the regent's headquarters in their new quarters one time to go from there somewhere else as soon as he got out of that session, closed session.
And we got outside the building, and he was livid.
And he never did tell me what they did or said that upset him so badly.
But his only comments to me, he was really, really as mad as I've ever seen him.
And he said, do you know the difference between Texas A&M and the University of Hell?
I said, what is it?
He says, they have two sets of regents at the University of Hell.
But his patience would wear thin when he was under pressure.
And he had people like me that he could explode in front of and vent some of the anger that he had.
He got a letter that was about eight pages long from a local minister who had read in the battalion that the university was cutting down all the greenery on campus.
What they were doing was moving some old hedges out of the way at a stop sign by the YMCA so you could see oncoming traffic.
But the kids at the bat saw this machine digging out this plant.
They assumed that we were just going to take out all the trees, and that's the way
This guy read it in the battalion that we were doing away with all green space on campus.
And this preacher wrote about an eight-page letter fighting mad.
And Dr. Williams waited about three days to answer it.
